Based on the problem statement and the special instructions provided, here's the Julia solution:

```julia
abstract type AbstractVehicle end

immutable Car <: AbstractVehicle end
immutable Motorcycle <: AbstractVehicle end
immutable Bus <: AbstractVehicle end
immutable Truck <: AbstractVehicle end

function ispersonal(veh::AbstractVehicle)
    if isa(veh, Car) || isa(veh, Motorcycle)
        return true
    else
        return false
    end
end

# Test the function
@test ispersonal(Car()) == true
@test ispersonal(Motorcycle()) == true
@test ispersonal(Bus()) == false
@test ispersonal(Truck()) == false
@test ispersonal(AbstractVehicle()) == false
```

This solution uses the given `AbstractVehicle` base type and creates subtypes `Car`, `Motorcycle`, `Bus`, and `Truck`. The `ispersonal` function checks the given `veh` argument's type using the `isa` function and returns `true` if it's a `Car` or `Motorcycle` and `false` otherwise. The function also handles any other subtypes of `AbstractVehicle` by defaulting to `false`.
